<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900621-0003</DOCNO><DOCID>900621-0003.</DOCID><HL>   House Panel Adopts   Measure to Let SEC   Fine Violators of Law</HL><DATE>06/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8</SO><IN>SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)</IN><GV>SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)CONGRESS (CNG)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- A House subcommittee approved legislationthat would expand the Securities and Exchange Commission'spower to impose fines on individuals and firms that violatesecurities laws.   The telecommunications and finance panel also passed abill aimed at curbing penny-stock fraud, after substantiallychanging provisions opposed by the SEC and the securitiesindustry. Both bills now move to the full Energy and CommerceCommittee.</LP><TEXT>   The civil-penalties bill, identical in most respects tolegislation recently passed by the Senate Banking Committee,would give the SEC power to impose monetary penalties foroffenses other than insider trading, for which the agencycurrently has fining power. The House bill also gives the SECthe power to issue cease-and-desist orders to enforce thesecurities laws. But compared with the Senate bill, the Housebill includes additional protections for parties subject tosuch orders to assure the target's right to due process.   In the penny-stock bill, the House subcommittee softened aprovision that would have required the creation of anelectronic system to disseminate penny-stock quotes. Therevised bill directs the SEC to adopt rules to improvedissemination of penny-stock quotes. The revised bill alsodirects the SEC to adopt rules providing for increaseddisclosure of information about companies that sell pennystocks to the public.   Moreover, a provision in the bill that would have bannedso-called blind pools and blank-check offerings was softenedto require the SEC only to increase disclosure requirementsfor such offerings. In both types of offerings, the issuersdon't have a business plan or specific assets.</TEXT></DOC>